ricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOne of the most significant transformations in twentieth-century Christianity is the emergence and development of Pentecostalism. With over five hundred million followers, it is the fastest-growing movement in the world. An incredibly diverse movement, it has influenced many sectors of Christianity, flourishing in Africa, Latin America, and Asia and having an equally significant effect on Canada. Bringing together a previously scattered and somewhat hidden literature, Canadian Pentecostalism provides the first comprehensive overview of the subject. The collection is broad in focus, examining classical Pentecostalism, charismatic movements in the Roman Catholic and mainline Protestant traditions, and neo-Pentecostalism. Contributing authors examine historical debates about the origins of the movement, the response of Pentecostalism to institutionalization and globalization, and the roles of women, indigenous peoples, and immigrants within the Canadian movement.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aHISTORY / Canada / General.2bisacsh1 aAlthouse, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeyer, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurkinshaw, Robert K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGiacomo, Michael Di, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuenther, Bruce L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHolm, Randall, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHolmes, Pamela M. S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHunt, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMittelstadt,